accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Access to the records is restricted. See Collection Contents for details.

Original born digital files, as well as preservation masters, may not be accessed due to their fragility. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exist request that they be made. Born digital files cannot be accessed remotely. System requirements include a Manuscripts and Archives computer and file viewing software.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The records consist of administrative files, correspondence, and survivor testimonies from the Fortunoff Video Archive for Holocaust Testimonies.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Fortunoff Video Archive for Holocaust Testimonies began as a New Haven, Connecticut community project called the Holocaust Survivors Film Project (HSFP). The HSFP was founded by Laurel Vlock, a television journalist and Dori Laub, a psychologist and child survivor of the Holocaust. William Rosenberg, the president of the New Haven chapter of the Farband, a Zionist labor organization, was also instrumental in the creation of the project. One of the first four survivors whose gave testimony to the project was married to Geoffrey Hartman, a professor of English and Comparative Literatures at Yale University and a child survivor who escaped Germany on a Kindertransport. He was instrumental in bringing the HSFP's testimonies to Yale in 1981, where it was established as part of Manuscripts and Archives. An endowment by Alan Fortunoff permanently established the archive, which was renamed in his honor to the Fortunoff Video Archive for Holocaust Testimonies.

The Fortunoff Archive records testimonies of survivors, witnesses and bystanders of Nazi persecution. This includes Jewish and non-Jewish witnesses, Sinti and Roma survivors, individuals hidden during the war, those who escaped before the end of the war, resisters and partisans, liberators, and aid workers who served in the DP camps after the war. The Fortunoff interview methodology emphasizes giving agency to the survivor or witness to tell and structure their story as they wish. In addition to recording testimonies in New Haven and other cities, the Fortunoff Archive formed affiliate projects in other states and countries, where interviewers trained by archive staff recorded testimonies and sent a copy to the Fortunoff Archive for preservation and use in teaching and research. Over time, 37 affiliate projects were established, including projects in Germany, France, Israel, Belgium, Slovakia and many more. The Fortunoff Archive also holds conferences and other events related to testimony and its impact on Holocaust and Genocide Studies.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Records from Box 20 are restricted until January 1, 2093. All other records are restricted until January 1, 2053.
